## 2) Prevent the dots (“circles”) from overrunning the width

Your dots are generated dynamically in JS (buttons appended into `#tDots`), so as you add more testimonials, more dot buttons appear. fileciteturn0file0  
The current CSS sets **large 44×44 px tap targets** (good for accessibility) but doesn’t allow wrapping, so a long row can overflow. fileciteturn0file1

**Easiest, CSS‑only fix (wrap to multiple rows and auto‑densify when many dots exist):**  
Append the following **at the very end** of `assets/css/corporate-1.9.5.css` so it overrides earlier rules.

```css
/* --- Dots: prevent overflow by allowing wrap and densifying when many --- */

/* Let dots wrap to multiple rows, keep centered */
.section--testimonials .t-dots {
  flex-wrap: wrap;          /* key change */
  row-gap: 6px;             /* comfortable vertical spacing between rows */
}

/* When there are ≥12 dots, shrink the 44×44 tap targets to 32×32 to save space */
.section--testimonials .t-dots:has(.t-dot:nth-child(n+12)) .t-dot {
  inline-size: 32px;
  block-size: 32px;
}
.section--testimonials .t-dots:has(.t-dot:nth-child(n+12)) .t-dot::before {
  inline-size: 10px;
  block-size: 10px;
}

/* Optional: fallback if a very old browser lacks :has() (Firefox <121 etc.) */
@supports not selector(:has(*)) {
  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .section--testimonials .t-dot {
      inline-size: 36px;
      block-size: 36px;
    }
  }
}
```

Why this works:

- `renderTestimonials(...)` builds one `<button class="t-dot">` per slide under `#tDots`. The `:has(.t-dot:nth-child(n+12))` selector flips the layout to a denser mode automatically once the count is large. No JS changes required. fileciteturn0file0  
- The dots container is already inside `.t-wrap` which is width‑limited, so wrapping avoids horizontal overflow while preserving hit targets. fileciteturn0file1

> **Alternative (if you prefer one row only):** switch to horizontal scrolling instead of wrapping:
> ```css
> .section--testimonials .t-dots {
>   flex-wrap: nowrap;
>   overflow-x: auto;
>   justify-content: flex-start; /* or center if you prefer */
>   -webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch;
> }
> .section--testimonials .t-dot { scroll-snap-align: center; }
> ```
> Wrapping is usually more discoverable than hidden horizontal scroll, so I recommend the wrap solution first.

