## 3) Selected dot: blue fill **inside** only, theme‑aware (dark in light mode, light in dark mode)

Right now you have **two different dot implementations** in the same CSS:

1) An older one that fills using `::after` (with a 2px inset) and a small target.  
2) A newer, accessible one that draws the dot with `::before` on a 44×44 button and changes both the fill and the ring to the same blue when selected. fileciteturn0file1

The overlap means a selected dot may get **two pseudo‑elements** (`::before` and `::after`) at once. Let’s neutralize the old one, then keep the ring contrast color and only fill the interior.

**Add these overrides at the end of `assets/css/corporate-1.9.5.css`:**

```css
/* Disable the legacy ::after fill so only the modern ::before dot is used */
.section--testimonials .t-dot::after { content: none; }

/* Selected state: fill interior with theme-blue, keep ring as high-contrast */
.section--testimonials .t-dot[aria-selected="true"]::before {
  background: var(--t-dot-active);  /* the blue interior */
  box-shadow: 0 0 0 2px var(--t-dot-ring); /* keep the ring black (light) / white (dark) */
}

/* Hover: don’t recolor the ring; keep the contrast outline */
.section--testimonials .t-dot:hover::before {
  transform: scale(1.15);
  box-shadow: 0 0 0 2px var(--t-dot-ring);
}
```

You already have theme‑aware tokens in place:

- **Light mode:** `--t-dot-ring: #000` (black outline) and `--primary: var(--light-primary) = #0057b8` (dark blue).  
- **Dark mode:** `--t-dot-ring: #fff` (white outline) and `--primary: var(--dark-primary) = #4ea1ff` (light blue).  
Your dot fill variable `--t-dot-active` is already set to `var(--primary)`, so the interior will be dark blue in light mode and light blue in dark mode exactly as requested. fileciteturn0file1

