## Patch: `assets/js/site-1.7.1.js`

**Add the helper inside `renderTestimonials(root, items)` (anywhere before you attach the dot click handlers is fine):**
```js
function scrollTestimonialsIntoView() {
  // Scroll target = the viewport wrapper of the carousel (falls back to the section)
  const target = root.querySelector('.t-viewport') || root;
  const headerEl = document.querySelector('.header');
  const headerH = headerEl ? headerEl.getBoundingClientRect().height : 0;

  // Compute absolute Y (page) and keep a little breathing room (8px)
  const y = target.getBoundingClientRect().top + window.scrollY - headerH - 8;

  // Respect reduced motion: disable smooth scroll if user prefers it
  const reduce =
    window.matchMedia &&
    window.matchMedia('(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)').matches;

  window.scrollTo({ top: Math.max(0, y), behavior: reduce ? 'auto' : 'smooth' });
}
```

**Change the dot click wiring (around where each dot is created):**
```diff
- dot.addEventListener("click", () => goTo(i));
+ dot.addEventListener("click", () => {
+   goTo(i);
+   // Scroll after the slide change so height/transform updates settle
+   requestAnimationFrame(scrollTestimonialsIntoView);
+ });
```

Where this lives: the dots are created in `renderTestimonials(...)` and currently have `dot.addEventListener("click", () => goTo(i));`. We’re just augmenting that behavior. fileciteturn0file0

---

## Optional (nice-to-have): CSS safety net for future use of `scrollIntoView`
If you ever switch to `target.scrollIntoView({block: 'start'})` instead of measuring the header in JS, give the testimonial viewport a theme‑aware margin for sticky headers:

```css
/* Place at the end of assets/css/corporate-1.9.5.css */
.section--testimonials .t-viewport { scroll-margin-top: 64px; }
@media (min-width: 1200px) {
  .section--testimonials .t-viewport { scroll-margin-top: 80px; }
}
```

Those values track your header sizes (56 px mobile, 72 px desktop) with a bit of padding. fileciteturn0file1

---

### (Optional) Apply the same scroll when arrows are used
If you want the **‹ / ›** buttons to behave the same way, add the call in their handlers too:
```js
btnPrev?.addEventListener("click", () => { goTo(index - 1); requestAnimationFrame(scrollTestimonialsIntoView); });
btnNext?.addEventListener("click", () => { goTo(index + 1); requestAnimationFrame(scrollTestimonialsIntoView); });
```
The buttons are already wired where `btnPrev`/`btnNext` are defined in the same function. fileciteturn0file0

---

**Why this approach:**  
- It keeps all behavior local to the carousel initializer (`renderTestimonials`), no global listeners. fileciteturn0file0  
- Sticky header is accounted for precisely at runtime rather than hardcoding a pixel value. Your header height differs by breakpoint (56 px vs 72 px). fileciteturn0file1  
- Reduced‑motion users get instant scrolling (no animation).  
- It works with your current HTML structure for the testimonials section. fileciteturn0file2

